Just in case you wanted a glimpse at just ONE of the reasons SAG-AFTRA went on strike ~ I give you the residuals that arrived in my mailbox today.
•
It is literally impossible to make a basic living as an actor. Period. I have been lucky to have found enough work to survive for 32 years. But it’s a daily grind that usually ends with a ‘no’ ~ and part-time jobs are a given to make ends meets. So, as a working class actor (us Blue Collar folks) - without residual income, I’d never have survived the ‘down times’ (and trust me there are WAY more of those than workdays). So, when residuals plummet to numbers like this ($1.82 doesn’t exactly pay the electric bill 😑)… Things need to change.
• 
The AMPTP’s offer to the @wgawest  and @sagaftra was “oblivion.” So, unified and proud… We said “no”.
• 
I hope the AMPTP comes back to the table soon ~ with civility and the acknowledgment that changes HAVE to be made ~ But till then, you’ll find us all on the picket lines. Melting from the heat, tired & hungry - but undauntedly resilient.
•
Thank you for all your support.

I had the privilege of spending Thanksgiving many years ago with  Paul Reubens - and a handful of other holiday misfits who didn’t have a place to go, including David Arquette and Chris Alvord (my dear friend @jonalvord brother who died not long after from complications from AIDS).
Other than Chris, I had not met either of these men, yet was welcomed in like family and got to spend a lovely afternoon laughing, telling stories and just enjoying not being alone on the holiday. The Paul I met ‘outside’ his public persona was a quiet, unassuming, incredibly kind and welcoming man - far removed from the public persona he created most famously by his character Pee-Wee Herman. It was an afternoon I still remember as a time when a group of strangers welcomed me among them as though I was a close friend. 
•
I only saw Paul one other time, several years later, at some event - but he smiled as soon as he saw me, gave me a ‘hug’ and asked how I’d been. 
•
Paul had an ability to bring joy to everything he did and was a comic genius. I’m so grateful I got to meet him - and all the times I got to watch him made me LAUGH OUT LOUD on screen. Good journey Paul… and thank you.
